			<li class="last"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a></li>
		</ul>
	</div>
		</header>
	<div class="a-column " id="a-col">
	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-611917 post type-post status-publish hentry category-corporate-governance-other-topics category-deal-professor category-food-beverage category-hedge-funds tag-barington-capital-group tag-boards-of-directors tag-darden-restaurants-inc tag-hedge-funds tag-otis-clarence-jr tag-red-lobster-restaurants tag-restaurants tag-shareholder-rights-and-activism tag-starboard-value-lp per-otis-clarence-jr des-boards-of-directors des-hedge-funds des-restaurants des-shareholder-rights-and-activism org-barington-capital-group org-darden-restaurants-inc org-red-lobster-restaurants org-starboard-value-lp" id="post-611917">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/hedge-funds/">Hedge Funds</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/columnists/deal-professor/">Deal Professor</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Battle Over Darden Leaves Little Room for Compromise</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Steven Davidoff Solomon			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-05-20T21:17:43+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 20, 2014 5:17 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 20, 2014 5:17 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/20/battle-over-darden-leaves-little-room-for-compromise/" data-title="Battle Over Darden Leaves Little Room for Compromise" data-description="A dispute over the sale of Red Lobster is only the latest in Dardenâs scorched-earth campaign to fight off activist investors, Steven Davidoff writes in the Deal Professor.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/business/dbpix-dealprof/dbpix-dealprof-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/business/dbpix-dealprof/dbpix-dealprof-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/21/business/dbpix-dealprof/dbpix-dealprof-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002891829" width="190" height="190" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="190"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Harry Campbell</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Can Clarence Otis Jr., the chief executive of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=DRI&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Darden Restaurants Inc">Darden Restaurants</a>, save himself by cutting off his claws?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thatâs the question raised by the announcement that Darden, which owns the Red Lobster and Olive Garden chains, plans to sell Red Lobster for $2.1 billion to Golden Gate Capital.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The sale was met by howls of protest from two hedge fund activists, Barington Capital and Starboard Value, with Baringtonâs chief executive, James A. Mitarotonda, calling it âunconscionableâ and a âfire sale.â The two funds have been lobbying for Darden to split off Olive Garden and Red Lobster into a company separate from its higher-value brands like the Capital Grille.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The dispute is only the latest in what has been Dardenâs scorched-earth campaign to fight off the activists.</p>
<div class="entry entry-section"><div class="w60"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/columnists/deal-professor/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/dealbook/icons/dealprof50.gif" /></a></div><h5><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/columnists/deal-professor/">Deal Professor</a></h5><h6><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/columnists/deal-professor/">View all posts</a></h6></div><!-- end .entry-section --><div class="entry entry-related"><h4>Related Links</h4>	<div class="entry-related">
		<ul>
					<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/05/16/darden-to-sell-red-lobster-for-2-1-billion/">Darden to Sell Red Lobster in a $2.1 Billion Deal (May 16, 2014)</a></li>
				</ul>
	</div>
	</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The initial opening for the hedge funds occurred because neither Olive Garden nor Red Lobster is doing particularly well. For its latest quarter, Darden announced that same-store sales in the United States had declined 5.4 percent at Olive Garden and 8.8 percent at Red Lobster. The chains are a victim of overexpansion and a weak economy as people shift from eating at sit-down restaurants to fast casual ones like <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=CMG&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Chipotle Mexican Grill Inc">Chipotle Mexican Grill</a>. And letâs face it, neither has the reputation of riding the health wave. Fun fact: Thirty percent of lunch orders at Olive Garden are for the all-you-can-eat salad, soup and pretty tasty breadsticks, at 140 calories each.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The activistsâ thinking in lumping Olive Garden together with Red Lobster is that it would put management focus on these low-growth businesses, allowing for a turnaround. The higher-growth brands, which include the Capital Grille, LongHorn Steakhouse and Bahama Breeze, would be in their own company. The activists also pointed out that this would better align customers of Olive Garden (average check, around $16) and Red Lobster (average check, $20) and not lump them with Capital Grille customers (average check, more than $70).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The battle was always likely to be uphill for the activists.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Darden is a bit of a corporate governance disaster, rated by ISS Quickscore at the top of its scale for governance risk. The company has built a 57-acre, $152 million headquarters in Orlando, Fla., that a company spokeswoman describes as âinspirationalâ and crucial to âshowcasingâ the companyâs brands. Mr. Otis was paid $6.3 million in 2013 while the company severely underperformed its peers, including Bloominâ Brands and the Cheesecake Factory, and the Standard &amp; Poorâs 500-stock index. Glass Lewis &amp; Company, the big proxy adviser, gives Darden a D on pay for performance. And Mr. Otis, who serves on four other boards, including that of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=VZ&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Verizon Communications Inc">Verizon Communications</a>, <a title="The New York Post article. " href="//nypost.com/2014/05/13/darden-ceo-has-too-much-on-his-plate-critics/">attended at least 84 board meetings last year</a>, according to The New York Post. Darden allows him to fly to those meetings on its private jet â perhaps explaining why he may not have enough time for the business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It also seems as if the company does not brook criticism well. In the past, the company has been criticized for preventing analysts from asking tough questions on conference calls.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And so Mr. Otisâs response to the activists has been consistent so far.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Darden amended its bylaws to add onerous requirements if an activist tried to nominate replacement directors, amendments for which the company is being sued in Florida. Darden also canceled its annual investor day, saying it was taking the show âon the roadâ and meeting independently with shareholders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To be fair, Mr. Otis and Dardenâs directors have also announced significant changes. Mr. Otisâs compensation has been reworked so it is no longer based on store openings â something that was cannibalizing store brands. The company has also reduced costs by $60 million and hired <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Goldman Sachs Group Inc">Goldman Sachs</a> to assist in a review of its operations. In addition, many of the changes to Olive Garden and Red Lobster are driven by economics and the simple fact that the American middle class is being squeezed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The latest battle erupted out of the results of its review, announced in March. Darden said that it would spin off or sell Red Lobster and keep everything else, including Olive Garden, which would halt store expansions and get a new campaign to freshen up the brand.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The activists viewed this as a mistake. They not only want to spin off both companies, they want to try some financial engineering to unleash the value of Red Lobster and Olive Gardenâs substantial real estate, either by putting it in a separately traded real estate investment trust or another transaction like a sale lease-back.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Starboard initiated a campaign to call a special meeting to vote on whether Red Lobster should be sold or spun off. On April 22, Starboard, which owns a 5.5 percent stake in Darden, submitted the request to the company with the agreement of 55.5 percent of Dardenâs shareholders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Darden stalled, and instead of scheduling the meeting, it announced the Red Lobster sale instead.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The activists protested again. âThe announced sale woefully undervalues Red Lobster and its real estate assets,â said Starboardâs chief executive, Jeffrey Smith. An analyst at Janney Capital Markets, Mark Kalinowski, summed it up in a note: âWho knew lobsters had middle fingers?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In its defense, Red Lobster says that the price is a good one. Its real estate will be sold separately for $1.5 billion, valuing the restaurant chain at about $600 million. A number of analysts agree that this is a fair price for the struggling business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Darden also contends that it asked the buyer, Golden Gate Capital, for a shareholder vote on the sale, but that it refused. That position is laughable, of course, because Golden Gate would obviously decline such a vote unless Darden demanded it â why take the risk?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the end, given that Darden was hardly promoting Red Lobster â in March it deemed the chain the no-growth child that it would get rid of â itâs hard to see how a blockbuster price was to be had.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When asked for comment, a spokeswoman for Darden said that the sale âmaximizes the value of Red Lobster and enables us to address key issues our shareholders have raised â the need to preserve the dividend and increase our focus on improving performance at Olive Garden.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For Barington and Starboard, the price may be right for the business as it is now, but the sale is coming at the worst time. They want shareholders to be able to participate in the turnaround and value. In the wake of the announcement, Dardenâs share price fell 4 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This reduces the battle to a question about management. Barington and Starboard seem to view this as a turnaround play and about persuading management to focus on that turnaround. Darden is saying the same thing but arguing that its focus should remain on everything but lobsters and shrimp.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One has to wonder why Mr. Otis â who has been chief executive for about nine years â waited so long to start focusing on the business instead of attending all those meetings. (A person close to the company said it was looking at the issues before Barington and Starboard started agitating.) If there is a general lesson here for other companies, that is the one. We are beyond the days when chief executives could relax in their expensive headquarters and not quickly find themselves the target of an activist. There is too much money at stake. Bad optics hurt.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Starboard appears set to nominate directors to Dardenâs board and continue its fight. The Red Lobster deal may be done, but shareholders will now have to begin sorting out the future management and whether they want to give Mr. Otis more time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In truth, the Red Lobster deal is a compromise that allowed everyone to focus on what they want, which is to manage the restaurants better, rather than focus on a financial trick to enhance value. But neither side seems in a compromising mood, and Darden and Mr. Otis seem to prefer hunkering down instead of engaging in any sort of talks. Dardenâs corporate governance also doesnât offer inspiration that the company is determined to focus on the future instead of preserving the past, even if it is pointed in the right direction.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That is a shame, because I will say that while I canât speak to the lobster, anyone who has had those breadsticks knows there has to be lots of value there.</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
